statement.p:
Let
A = \mat{1 1; 0 1}
and let T(x) = Ax, so T is a shear in the x-direction.  Find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of A without doing any computations.

solution.p:
          In equations, we have

            A\vec{x y} = \mat{1 1; 0 1}\vec{x y} = \vec{x+y y}.

          This tells us that a shear takes a vector and adds its y-coordinate to its x-coordinate.  Since the x-coordinate changes but not the y-coordinate, this tells us that any vector v with nonzero y-coordinate cannot be collinear with Av and the origin.

\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes, scale=1, baseline]
  \draw[grid lines] (-2,-2) grid (2,2);

  \draw[seq2] (-1,-2) -- (1,2);
  \point[seq2, "$v$" {above left, text=seq2}] (b) at (.5,1);
  \point[seq2, "$Av$" {text=seq2, below}] (Tb) at (1.5,1);
  \draw[|->, shorten=2pt] (b) -- (Tb);
  \point["0" above left] at (0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

          On the other hand, any vector v on the x-axis has zero y-coordinate, so it is not moved by A.  Hence v is an eigenvector with eigenvalue 1.

\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes, scale=1, baseline]
  \draw[grid lines] (-2,-2) grid (2,2);
  \draw[seq3, thick] (-2,0) to (2,0);

  \begin{scope}[arrows={|->}, shorten=2pt, font=\small]
  \point[seq3, "$w$" {text=seq3,inner sep=3pt, anchor=-35}] (c) at (1,0);
  \point[seq3, "$Aw$" {text=seq3,inner sep=3pt, anchor=-145}] (c) at (1,0);
  \draw (c) to[out=-125, in=-55, looseness=40] (c);
  \point["0" above] at (0,0);
  \end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}

          Accordingly, all eigenvectors of A lie on the x-axis, and have eigenvalue 1.

          If v is any nonzero vector, then Av is rotated by an angle of 90^\circ from v.  Therefore, Av is not on the same line as v, so v is not an eigenvector.  And of course, the zero vector is never an eigenvector.

\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes, scale=1, baseline]
  \draw[grid lines] (-2,-2) grid (2,2);

  \draw[seq2] (-1,-2) -- (1,2);
  \point[seq2, "$v$" {below right, text=seq2}] (b) at (.5,1);
  \point[seq2, "$Av$" {text=seq2, below}] (Tb) at (-1, .5);
  \draw[|->, shorten=3pt] (b) arc[radius={sqrt(5/4)}, start angle={atan2(2,1)}, delta angle=90] (Tb);
  \point["0" below right] at (0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

          Therefore, this matrix has no eigenvectors and eigenvalues.

subsection.p:
Let A be an n\times n matrix, and let \lambda be a scalar. The eigenvectors with eigenvalue \lambda, if any, are the nonzero solutions of the equation Av=\lambda v. We can rewrite this equation as follows:
\begin{split} \amp Av = \lambda v \\ \iff\quad \amp Av - \lambda v = 0 \\ \iff\quad \amp Av - \lambda I_nv = 0 \\ \iff\quad \amp(A - \lambda I_n)v = 0. \end{split}
Therefore, the eigenvectors of A with eigenvalue \lambda, if any, are the nontrivial solutions of the matrix equation (A-\lambda I_n)v = 0, i.e., the nonzero vectors in \Nul(A-\lambda I_n). If this equation has no nontrivial solutions, then \lambda is not an eigenvector of A.

Eigenspaceis a solution set
The above observation is important because it says that finding the eigenvectors for a given eigenvalue means solving a homogeneous system of equations.  For instance, if

  A = \mat{7 1 3; -3 2 -3; -3 -2 -1},

then an eigenvector with eigenvalue \lambda is a nontrivial solution of the matrix equation
\mat{7 1 3; -3 2 -3; -3 -2 -1}\vec{x y z} = \lambda \vec{x y z}.
This translates to the system of equations

  \syseq{
  7x + y + 3z = \lambda x ;
  -3x + 2y - 3z = \lambda y ;
  -3x - 2y - z = \lambda z
  }
  \quad\xrightarrow{\phantom{MMM}}\quad
  \syseq{
  (7-\lambda)x + y + 3z = 0 ;
  -3x + (2-\lambda)y - 3z = 0 ;
  -3x - 2y + (-1-\lambda)z = 0\rlap.
  }

This is the same as the homogeneous matrix equation

  \mat{7-\lambda, 1 3; -3 2-\lambda, -3; -3 -2 -1-\lambda}\vec{x y z} = 0,

i.e., (A-\lambda I_3)v = 0.
